Echidna was the 'Mother of All Monsters,' the half-woman, half-serpent creature who dwelt
in a cave beneath the earth, immortal and ageless forever.
From the waist up she was a beautiful woman with gleaming eyes;
below she was a coiling, mottled serpent of immense size.
With Typhon, the greatest of all monsters, she produced a terrifying brood:
Cerberus, the three-headed watchdog of the Underworld;
the Lernaean Hydra, the multi-headed water-serpent slain by Heracles;
the Chimera, the fire-breathing lion-goat-serpent hybrid;
the Sphinx of Thebes, who devoured those who failed her riddle;
the Nemean Lion, whose hide was impervious to all weapons;
and Orthus, the two-headed dog who guarded the cattle of Geryon.
Some traditions also made her mother of the Colchian Dragon, the Caucasian Eagle that tormented Prometheus,
and the Cretan Bull.
The heroes of Greece built their reputations largely by defeating the children of Echidna.
Heracles alone slew the Hydra, the Nemean Lion, and Orthus.
Bellerophon killed the Chimera; Oedipus defeated the Sphinx.
Echidna herself was said by Hesiod to be immortal and ageless: the gods left her alive
to test the heroes of the future.
She was eventually killed in her sleep by the hundred-eyed giant Argus.
Echidna — beautiful and terrible — was the dark mother from whose womb all the great ordeals of heroes came.
